05035nam a22008775i 9781400846368DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2013    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008463687 a10.1515/97814008463682doi  a(DE-B1597)453918  a(OCoLC)843882796  a(OCoLC)979686147  a(OCoLC)984682157  a(OCoLC)987949487  a(OCoLC)992507633  a(OCoLC)999360018  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJC585b.P444 2017 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a323.442231 aPhillips, Anne, eauthor.10aOur Bodies, Whose Property? /cAnne Phillips.  aCore Textbook 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. What's So Special about the Body? -- tChapter Two. Property Models of Rape -- tChapter Three. Bodies for Rent? The Case of Commercial Surrogacy -- tChapter Four. Spare Parts and Desperate Need -- tChapter Five. The Individualism of Property Claims -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNo one wants to be treated like an object, regarded as an item of property, or put up for sale. Yet many people frame personal autonomy in terms of self-ownership, representing themselves as property owners with the right to do as they wish with their bodies. Others do not use the language of property, but are similarly insistent on the rights of free individuals to decide for themselves whether to engage in commercial transactions for sex, reproduction, or organ sales. Drawing on analyses of rape, surrogacy, and markets in human organs, Our Bodies, Whose Property? challenges notions of freedom based on ownership of our bodies and argues against the normalization of markets in bodily services and parts. Anne Phillips explores the risks associated with metaphors of property and the reasons why the commodification of the body remains problematic. What, she asks, is wrong with thinking of oneself as the owner of one's body? What is wrong with making our bodies available for rent or sale? What, if anything, is the difference between markets in sex, reproduction, or human body parts, and the other markets we commonly applaud? Phillips contends that body markets occupy the outer edges of a continuum that is, in some way, a feature of all labor markets. But she also emphasizes that we all have bodies, and considers the implications of this otherwise banal fact for equality. Bodies remind us of shared vulnerability, alerting us to the common experience of living as embodied beings in the same world. Examining the complex issue of body exceptionalism, Our Bodies, Whose Property? demonstrates that treating the body as property makes human equality harder to comprehend.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aCapitalism. 0aHuman body. 0aLiberty. 0aProperty. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066258008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045953140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400846368zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400846368.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-045953-1  Princeton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066258-0  PUP eBook-Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL